    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-02T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-02T10:00:00-05:00" n="118"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d118">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.48 Refugees/1832: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-02T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 2, 1939—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 2—9:53 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1378. Winterton has requested the Foreign Office to ascertain the views of the
                    United States Government as to the future of the Intergovernmental Committee.
                        Lothian<note n="74" xml:id="d118fn74">The Marquess of Lothian, British
                        Ambassador in the United States.</note> will doubtless raise the question in
                    due course. Winterton expects to resign in any event. Emerson has offered his
                    services to the British Government and if they are accepted he will presumably
                    resign from both his refugee offices.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
